n17_commentsSome of the sentences from the bot were unnatural. Like I don’t often hear someone say to me like “an amigo who likes leer”. If they use the verb in Spanish but the words immediately preceding are in English, the addition of English “to” sounds more natural like “to leer”. And at least in my experience speaking with other bilingual friends the switching is usually either half of the sentence or alternating sentences. Usually when an English word pops in my head first I switch to English or vice-versa. Rarely do I just use one word in the other language unless it’s pretty specific to that language like güera or technical/internet terms. But I found myself doing it along with the robot! I think that kind of mirroring also guides the two languages in my normal conversations, as well. At a previous job, My boss spoke to me in both Spanish and English and I would often switch when she did. But, a co-worker only spoke Spanish so I never used Spanglish with her.
